-- Belgacom, Gamesa, Iberdrola, Brachytherapy, Endesa: Europe Equity Preview
-- B y   N i k o l a j   G a m m e l t o f t
-- 2010-12-28T05:00:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-27/belgacom-gamesa-iberdrola-lafarge-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are from the previous close.  The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  fell 0.8 percent to 279.18. The
 Stoxx 50 Index  decreased 0.9 percent to 2,629.37. The  Euro Stoxx
50 Index , a benchmark for nations using the euro, fell 1.2
percent to 2,826.51.  Belgacom SA  (BELG BB): Chief Executive Officer Didier
Bellens sold 1.63 million euros ($2.14 million) of the largest
Belgian telephone company’s stock, according to a regulatory
filing. Bellens sold 63,925 shares for an average 25.55 euros
apiece in trades on Dec. 20 and Dec. 21. Belgacom declined 0.3
percent to 25.52 euros.  Banco Comercial Portugues SA  (BCP PL): Portugal’s biggest
publicly traded bank by assets said it completed the sale of 95
percent of Turkey-based Millennium Bank AS to Credit Europe Bank
NV, a unit of Fiba Holding AS, for an adjusted 58.9 million
euros ($77.4 million). The shares fell 1.3 percent to 60 euro
cents.  Gamesa Corporacion Tecnologica SA  (GAM SM): Iberdrola SA
increased its stake in Gamesa to 18.833 percent, according to a
regulatory filing. Iberdrola has acquired more than 4 percent of
Spain’s largest wind-turbine maker since October. The shares
dropped 0.4 percent to 5.73 euros.  Iberdrola SA  (IBE SM): Spain’s largest utility may move as
Spain approved a 9.8 percent increase in electricity bills for
more than 20 million consumers from Jan. 1, the biggest increase
since 1983, El Pais reported citing the industry ministry. The
government also approved an average 3.93 percent increase in
natural gas bills, the newspaper said. Iberdrola shares 1.3
percent to 5.84 euros.  Endesa SA  (ELE SM): Shares of the Spanish utility
controlled by Italy’s Enel SpA fell 0.4 percent to 19.52 euros.
 Gas Natural SDG SA  (GAS SM) shares fell 0.7 percent to 11.45
euros.  International Brachytherapy SA  (IBT BB): The radiotherapy
unit of Eckert & Ziegler AG agreed to buy Sonotech GmbH, a
German maker of medical planning software, for an undisclosed
amount. Brachytherapy gained 1.5 percent to 2.72 euros.  Lafarge SA  (LG FP): The world’s biggest cement maker said
it sold concrete and aggregates plants in Portugal, Switzerland
and France for 120 million euros. Shares rose less than 0.1
percent to 46.95 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Nikolaj Gammeltoft  in New York at 
